@NODE "main"  "GrepPPC.guide ©2005 User Manual:"
@TOC "Contents"
  This manual is intended as an aid in using the @{B}GrepPPC@{UB}
  program.  It is not intended to be used as a primer on the uses of @{pgmName}.
  @{FG SHINE}In other words, you will only find information in this
  file, NOT Wisdom! @{FG TEXT}
  
  @{B}GrepPPC V2.0@{UB} was compiled from the @{B}grep-src.lha@{UB} distribution found on @{B}aminet@{UB} & is a 
  program that searches for patterns of text in files.

  In order to use @{B}GrepPPC@{UB}, you have to have the @{" Requirements " LINK "requirement"}.
      
  @{" File System Configuration " LINK "DiskConfig"} 

  @{" Warranty     " LINK "warranty"}
  @{" Distribution " LINK "distribution"}

  @{" Author              " LINK "Author"} 
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE "manualPage" "grep Manual Page:"
@{B}
GREP (1)                    1992 September 10                     GREP (1) @{UB}
@{FG SHINE}
NAME   @{FG TEXT}
        grep, egrep, fgrep - print lines matching a pattern 
@{FG SHINE}
SYNOPOSIS   @{FG TEXT}
        @{pgmName} [-[[ AB ]] num ] [ -[CEFGVBchilnsvwx ]] [ -e ] @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI} | -f file ] [files...] 
@{FG SHINE}
DESCRIPTION   @{FG TEXT}
        Grep searches the named input files (or standard input 
        if no files are named, or the file name @{B}-@{UB} is  given) for
        lines containing a match to the given @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI}. By 
        default, @{pgmName} prints the matching lines.

        There are three major variants of @{pgmName}, controlled by the following options:  

        @{B}-G@{UB} Interpret @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI} as a basic regular expression (see below).  
	   This is the default.  

        @{B}-E@{UB} Interpret @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI} as an extended regular expression (see below).  

        @{B}-F@{UB} Interpret @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI} as a list of fixed strings, separated by newlines, 
	   any of which is to be matched.  

        In addition, two variant programs egrep and fgrep are available.@{B}   
	(But not in this Amiga distribution -- JTS). @{UB}
	Egrep is similiar (but not identical) to @{B}grep -E@{UB}, and is compatible  
	with the historical Unix egrep.  Fgrep is the same as @{B}grep -F@{UB}.

        All variants of @{pgmName} understand the following @{" options: " LINK "options"} 
@{FG SHINE}
REGULAR EXPRESSIONS   @{FG TEXT}

        A regular expression is a @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI} that describes a set of strings.  Regular  
	expressions are constructed analagously to arithmetic expressions, by using 
	various operators to combine smaller expressions.  

        Grep understands two different versions of regular expression syntax:  
	    @{B}basic@{UB} and @{B}extended@{UB}.
	    
	In GNU @{pgmName}, there is no difference in available functionality using either syntax.   
	In other implementations, basic regular expressions are less powerful.  The following
        description applies to extended regular expressions; differences for basic regular 
	expressions are summarized afterwards.  

        The fundamental building blocks are the regular expressions that match a single 
	character.  Most characters, including all letters and digits, are regular 
	expressions that match themselves.  Any metacharacter with special meaning may be
        quoted by preceding it with a backslash (@{B}\\@{UB}).  

        A list of characters enclosed by @{B}[@{UB} and @{B}]@{UB} matches any single character in that list; 
	if the first character of the list is the caret @{B}^@{UB} then it matches any character not
        in the list.  For example, the regular expression @{B}[0123456789]@{UB} matches any single  
	digit.  A range of ASCII characters may be specified by giving the first and last
        characters, separated by a hyphen.   Finally, certain named classes of characters are 
	predefined.  Their names are self explanatory, and they are 
	@{FG SHINE}
	    [:alnum:] [:alpha:] [:cntrl:] [:digit:] [:graph:]
            [:lower:] [:print:] [:punct:] [:space:] [:upper:]@{FG TEXT} 
	    and  @{FG SHINE}[:xdigit:]@{FG TEXT}.

        For example, @{B}[[:alnum:]]@{UB} means @{B}[0-9A-Za-z]@{UB}, except the latter form is dependent  
	upon the ASCII character encoding, whereas @{B}[[:alnum:]]@{UB} is portable.  (Note that the
        brackets in these class names are part of the symbolic names, and must be included 
	in addition to the brackets delimiting the bracket list.)  Most metacharacters lose  
	their special meaning inside lists.  To include a literal @{B}]@{UB} place it first in the 
        list.   Similarly, to include a literal @{B}^@{UB} place it anywhere but first.  Finally, 
	to include a literal @{B}-@{UB} place it last.

        The period @{B}.@{UB} matches any single character.  The symbol @{B}w@{UB} is a synonym for 
	@{B}[[:alnum:]]@{UB} and @{B}W@{UB} is a synonym for @{B}[^[:alnum]]@{UB}.

        The caret @{B}^@{UB} and the dollar sign @{B}$@{UB} are metacharacters that respectively match the 
	empty string at the beginning and end of a line.  The symbols @{B}<@{UB} and @{B}>@{UB} respectively 
	match the empty string at the beginning and end of a word.  The symbol @{B}b@{UB} matches the 
	empty string at the edge of a word, and @{B}B@{UB} matches the empty string provided it's not 
	at the edge of a word.  

        A regular expression matching a single character may be followed by one of several 
	repetition operators: 

        @{B}?@{UB} The preceding item is optional and matched at most once.  

        @{B}*@{UB} The preceding item will be matched zero or more times.  

        @{B}+@{UB} The preceding item will be matched one or more times.  

        @{B}{ n }@{UB}  The preceding item is matched exactly ntimes.  

        @{B}{ n ,}@{UB} The preceding item is matched nor more times.  

        @{B}{, m }@{UB} The preceding item is optional and is matched at most m times.  

        @{B}{ n , m }@{UB} The  preceding item is matched at least n times, but not more than 
	          m times.  

        Two regular expressions may be concatenated; the resulting regular expression  
	matches any string formed by concatenating two substrings that respectively match   
	the concatenated subexpressions.  

        Two regular expressions may be joined by the infix operator @{B}|@{UB}; the resulting 
	regular expression matches any string matching either subexpression.  

        Repetition takes precedence over concatenation, which in turn takes precedence over 
	alternation.  A whole subexpression may be enclosed in parentheses to override 
	these precedence rules.  

        The backreference @{B}n@{UB}, where @{B}n@{UB} is a single digit, matches the substring previously
	matched by the nth parenthesized subexpression of the regular expression.  (I assume
	that this is referring to the extended mode of operation!  JTS)

        In basic regular expressions the metacharacters @{B}? + { | ( )@{UB} lose their  
	special meaning; instead use the backslashed versions @{B}\\? \\+ \\{ \\| \\( \\)@{UB}.

        In egrep the metacharacter @{B}{@{UB} loses its special meaning; instead use @{B}\\{@{UB}.
@{FG SHINE}
DIAGNOSTICS   @{FG TEXT}

        Normally, exit status is 0 if matches were found, and 1 if no matches were found.    
	(The @{B}-v@{UB} option inverts the sense of the exit status.)  Exit status is 2 if there 
	were syntax errors in the @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI}, inaccessible input files, or other system
        errors.  
@{FG SHINE}
BUGS   @{FG TEXT}

        Email bug reports to @{B}bug-gnu-utils\@prep.ai.mit.edu@{UB}.  
	Be sure to include the word @{FG SHINE}grep@{FG TEXT} somewhere in the @{B}Subject:@{UB} field.  

        Large repetition counts in the @{B}{ m , n }@{UB} construct may cause @{pgmName} to use
        lots of memory.  In addition, certain other obscure regular expressions  
	require exponential time and space, and may cause @{pgmName} to run out of memory.  
        Backreferences are very slow, and may require exponential time.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE "options" "grep command line arguments:"
@{FG SHINE}
SYNOPOSIS  @{FG TEXT}
        @{pgmName} [-[[AB]] num] [-[CEFGVBchilnsvwx]] [-e] @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI} | -f file ] [files...] 
@{FG SHINE}
OPTIONS @{FG TEXT}
        All variants of @{pgmName} understand the following options: 

        @{B}- num@{UB} Matches will be printed with numlines of leading and trailing 
	      context.  However, @{pgmName} will never print any given line more than once.  

        @{B}-A num@{UB} Print numlines of trailing context after matching lines.  

        @{B}-B num@{UB} Print numlines of leading context before matching lines.  

        @{B}-C@{UB} Equivalent to @{B}-2@{UB}.

        @{B}-V@{UB} Print the version number of @{pgmName} to standard error.  This version  
	   number should be included in all bug reports (see below).  

        @{B}-b@{UB} Print the byte offset within the input file before each line of output.  

        @{B}-c@{UB} Suppress normal output; instead print a count of matching lines for
	   each input file.  With the @{B}-v@{UB} option (see below), count non-matching lines.  

        @{B}-e pattern@{UB} Use @{B}pattern@{UB} as the @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI}; useful to protect patterns beginning 
	   with @{B}-@{UB}.

        @{B}-f@{UB} filename Obtain the @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI} from file.

        @{B}-h@{UB} Suppress the prefixing of filenames on output when multiple files are searched.  

        @{B}-i@{UB} Ignore case distinctions in both the @{B}pattern@{UB} and the input files.  

        @{B}-L@{UB} Suppress normal output; instead print the name of each input file from  
	   which no output would normally have been printed.  

        @{B}-l@{UB} Suppress normal output; instead print the name of each input file from which 
	   output would normally have been printed.  In other words, print the filename
	   of each file that has matches to the supplied @{I}@{B}pattern@{UB}@{UI}.

        @{B}-n@{UB} Prefix each line of output with the line number within its input file.  

        @{B}-q@{UB} Quiet; suppress normal output.  

        @{B}-s@{UB} Suppress error messages about nonexistent or unreadable files.  

        @{B}-v@{UB} Invert the sense of matching, to select non-matching lines.  

        @{B}-w@{UB} Select only those lines containing matches that form whole words.  The test  
	   is that the matching substring must either be at the beginning of the line,  
	   or preceded by a non-word constituent character.  Similarly, it must be either 
	at the end of the line or followed by a non-word constituent character.  
	Word-constituent characters are letters, digits, and the underscore.  

        @{B}-x@{UB} Select only those matches that exactly match the whole line.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE DiskConfig "File System Configuration:"

  Simply click on the @{B}GrepPPC@{UB} Install Icon to install the program.

  There might be more files in some directories, so this list represents only
  the minimum that you received.
     
  This is the layout of the GrepPPC environment that you need to have
  in order to suppress un-wanted requester activity:
	   
  The install script will create a Directory called @{B}grep@{UB} with the following
  contents:

    grepPPC     (also copied to your commands/programs (C:) directory as @{pgmName})
@{FG SHINE}    
  Source/ @{FG TEXT}
    alloca.c
    config.h        (gcc & AmigaOS4-dependent #defines)
    dfa.c             
    dfa.h 
    getopt.c
    getopt.h          
    getpagesize.h
    grep.c            
    grep.h
    kwset.c
    kwset.h
    MakeFile        (For gcc V2.95+ & SAS-C V6.58)  
    obstack.c
    obstack.h
    regex.c
    regex.h
    search.c

    configure       (These are not really needed for the Amiga OS):
    configure.in
    INSTALL
    install-sh        
    INSTALL.VMS
    make.com
    Makefile.in    
@{FG SHINE}
  Documentation/ @{FG TEXT}
    Grep.guide    will be placed in your documents directory (Help:) also.
    grep.man      (original nroff-formatted man page file).
    COPYING       (GNU GPL License).
    AUTHORS       (Those that are responsible for writing grep itself.) 
    ChangeLog
    MANIFEST
    NEWS              
    Product-Info
    PROJECTS
    README    
@ENDNODE

@NODE requirement "GrepPPC requirements:"
@NEXT distribution
@PREV main

   @{B}REQUIREMENTS
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{UB}

   AmigaOne PowerPC & AmigaOS4+
   (680x0 versions available upon request, or compile it yourself, you have the source!) 

   Hard disk space (1 MB or more).
   
@ENDNODE

